            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Akemi Miller\u2019s life is a curated collection of dualities. The daughter of a Kyoto-born ceramicist and a third-generation Californian architect, she grew up in San Jose surrounded by both shoji screens and mid-century modern furniture. Her childhood was a quiet study in contrasts: the disciplined grace of her mother\u2019s ikebana arrangements and the bold, clean lines of her father\u2019s blueprints. This fusion of Japanese minimalism and California modernism became the bedrock of her aesthetic sensibilities.\n\nHer educational journey was a deliberate move towards defining her own space in the art world. After completing her undergraduate degree at UC Berkeley, she moved to New York for her graduate program in Art History and Curatorial Studies, eager to immerse herself in the heart of the American art scene. She spent her early career in prestigious but conventional museums, finding the pace stifling. The turning point came a decade ago when she was offered a position at a groundbreaking new cultural center in San Francisco that blended visual art with culinary experiences and performance. She took the risk, leaving an established institution for a dynamic startup. It was here she thrived, eventually rising to Director of Exhibitions.\n\nNow 46 and amicably divorced for years, Akemi\u2019s life is anchored in her meticulously designed Hayes Valley condo. Her daily routine begins with genmaicha tea and a review of international art journals. The 3.8-mile Muni ride to her SoMa office is her time for reflection, watching the city\u2019s diverse characters pass by. Her work is a whirlwind of planning, artist negotiations, and donor dinners, a high-stakes performance she executes with practiced ease. Her social life is an extension of her work\u2014a tight-knit circle of artists, chefs, and designers.\n\nHer connection to San Francisco is profound; the city is both her canvas and her muse. She sees the fog rolling over Twin Peaks with the same appreciation as a Hokusai print. Her deeper aspiration is to use her position to launch a major retrospective on the evolution of Japanese-American art in California, a project that would be the ultimate tribute to her own heritage and a legacy for the city she calls home."
        },
